title: For Sale:  Custom Ruger Bisley 45
postcontent: I have a really nice custom Ruger Bisley for sale.  This is an early model circa 1987, that has had some nice mods done to it.  Barrel has been shortened to 5.5" with the warning removed and a taller site added.  Full length ejector rod housing was added to finish the look.  The trigger is so smooth it makes shot placement very easy.  The cylinder spins freely now, so loading is made easy as well.  Also added was a John Gallagher cylinder pin so there is no jumping of the pin when firing the heavier loads.  This is a very nice Bisley, even retaining some of the plum color on the loading gate.  Common to all early Rugers and give it that added nostalgic look.   This is set up for the pounding 300grn colt loads only these strong Rugers can handle and made easy on the hands with the Bisley style grip frame.  Tight revolver ready for target shooting or this years hunting season.    When the full length ejector rod housing was added, the screw hole penetrated the bore.  This is a small hole in the last 1/4 of the bore and from my experience has not affected the accuracy of this pistol at all.  Ejector rod screw has not backed out, which is common on Blackhawks, so it's a good fit.  While not effecting accuracy it does need to be known to any buyer.  Would be happy to allow a potential buyer to shoot it first at their cost for ammo and range time.    Looking to get $800 for this nice example.  You could not get this built for under $1,000 these days and you would wait months to get it.  Partial trade for 45-70 Ruger 357 Flat Top or?  Cash price $750 OBO

title: For Sale:  Gewehr 1888/05 Commission Rifle
postcontent: Manufacturer: Ludwig Loewe & CompanyModel: Gewehr 1888/05 Commission RifleLocation of Manufacture: Berlin, GermanyYear of Manufacture: 1890The rifle is historically significant. During the arms race of the late 1800's, the German Empire designed and built the Gewehr 1888 as the countries first infantry rifle designed for a smokeless powder cartridge. In 1905 the Gewehr 1888s were rechambered for the new 7.92X57mm Mauser Spitzer cartridge and renamed the Gewehr 1888/05. The reciever was stamped with an "S" to signify that the barrel was rechambered. The barrel is unique because it was covered in a sheet metal tube to keep the barrel off the wood to improve accuracy. Text only please: 315-955-two-eight-eight-six
